WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.650 align:middle line:10%
[BACKGROUND MUSIC]

00:00:11.650 --> 00:00:14.220 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA GARR: Hi, I'm Lisa Garr,
host of "Gaiam Inspirations,"

00:00:14.220 --> 00:00:16.510 align:middle line:10%
and we are broadcasting
here from beautiful Denver,

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:17.650 align:middle line:10%
Colorado.

00:00:17.650 --> 00:00:20.720 align:middle line:10%
So did you know that you can
literally talk your way out

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:21.480 align:middle line:10%
of stress?

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:25.060 align:middle line:84%
That you can actually
heal through communication

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:28.310 align:middle line:84%
instead of medication
in many cases?

00:00:28.310 --> 00:00:30.530 align:middle line:90%
Dr. Neha Sangwan is with me.

00:00:30.530 --> 00:00:34.270 align:middle line:84%
Her goal is to create
self-care through health care.

00:00:34.270 --> 00:00:36.540 align:middle line:84%
She's known as a doctor
of communications,

00:00:36.540 --> 00:00:39.320 align:middle line:84%
but she's also a doctor
of internal medicine

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:43.470 align:middle line:84%
and a physician whose main
prescription is communication.

00:00:43.470 --> 00:00:44.274 align:middle line:90%
It is, isn't it?

00:00:44.274 --> 00:00:45.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NEHA SANGWAN: It is.

00:00:45.190 --> 00:00:47.750 align:middle line:84%
At least it's the front
line prescription.

00:00:47.750 --> 00:00:51.540 align:middle line:84%
Which is, I look there before
I prescribe someone medication,

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:53.520 align:middle line:84%
whereas I think our
medical system goes

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:54.637 align:middle line:90%
the opposite direction.

00:00:54.637 --> 00:00:55.220 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:00:55.220 --> 00:00:57.947 align:middle line:84%
So how did you, as a physician
of internal medicine,

00:00:57.947 --> 00:00:59.780 align:middle line:84%
where people are coming
to you with ailments

00:00:59.780 --> 00:01:01.575 align:middle line:84%
and usually
intestinally related,

00:01:01.575 --> 00:01:06.240 align:middle line:84%
how did you relink that
to their communication?

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:08.830 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: So really, of course,
right, doctor heal thyself.

00:01:08.830 --> 00:01:11.450 align:middle line:90%
It was me and my patients.

00:01:11.450 --> 00:01:13.650 align:middle line:10%
But initially I think
people's signals

00:01:13.650 --> 00:01:15.640 align:middle line:10%
come to them as whispers.

00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:17.770 align:middle line:10%
So they just hear a little
something, you know?

00:01:17.770 --> 00:01:19.564 align:middle line:90%
Mine was throat constriction.

00:01:19.564 --> 00:01:20.980 align:middle line:10%
So my throat would
just constrict,

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:23.374 align:middle line:10%
and then after a while
I couldn't breathe.

00:01:23.374 --> 00:01:25.040 align:middle line:10%
And it almost felt
like a constant sense

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:26.740 align:middle line:10%
of gasping for air.

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:29.730 align:middle line:10%
And then I went to a doctor
convinced that this throat

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:31.330 align:middle line:10%
constriction was a tumor, right?

00:01:31.330 --> 00:01:34.120 align:middle line:84%
Because I'd been reading about
it, learning about it, right?

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:36.250 align:middle line:84%
Seeing all these
people who had it.

00:01:36.250 --> 00:01:38.860 align:middle line:84%
And they put me out
under anesthesia,

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:43.180 align:middle line:84%
put a camera down my throat,
and said no, you look great.

00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:44.660 align:middle line:90%
OK, you're on your way.

00:01:44.660 --> 00:01:46.760 align:middle line:84%
Two years later I had
convinced another doctor

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:50.670 align:middle line:84%
to do the same thing who then
said to me, you look great.

00:01:50.670 --> 00:01:51.870 align:middle line:90%
I think it's stress.

00:01:51.870 --> 00:01:54.500 align:middle line:90%
And I thought, stress?

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:55.650 align:middle line:90%
Are you crazy?

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:58.460 align:middle line:84%
And I just went along my
way until I burned out.

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:02.350 align:middle line:84%
And when I burned out in 2004,
it became very clear to me

00:02:02.350 --> 00:02:05.750 align:middle line:84%
I was in the wrong job, I was
in the wrong relationship.

00:02:05.750 --> 00:02:07.197 align:middle line:90%
It just wasn't a good fit.

00:02:07.197 --> 00:02:08.780 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Where do you
think it started?

00:02:08.780 --> 00:02:10.849 align:middle line:90%
Take me back to childhood.

00:02:10.849 --> 00:02:11.890 align:middle line:90%
Where did that come from?

00:02:11.890 --> 00:02:14.420 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: So I think
it started quite young.

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:21.180 align:middle line:84%
I would say I had a very
colorful, creative, loud older

00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:22.340 align:middle line:90%
sister.

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:25.770 align:middle line:84%
And all I wanted was
her affection and love.

00:02:25.770 --> 00:02:28.940 align:middle line:84%
And for whatever reason, she
wasn't very interested in me.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:30.300 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:30.800 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:34.640 align:middle line:84%
I'm a little bit of like a gnat,
an annoying pest, an 18 month

00:02:34.640 --> 00:02:38.260 align:middle line:84%
younger sister who just wants
to do everything you want to do.

00:02:38.260 --> 00:02:42.400 align:middle line:84%
And so I think that
was when I started

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:46.950 align:middle line:84%
to learn that my voice
wasn't important.

00:02:46.950 --> 00:02:49.170 align:middle line:84%
And I started to learn
from the Indian community

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:50.500 align:middle line:90%
that I grew up in.

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:52.350 align:middle line:90%
My family's amazing.

00:02:52.350 --> 00:02:54.945 align:middle line:84%
And they come with
cultural beliefs.

00:02:54.945 --> 00:02:57.070 align:middle line:84%
You know, it's about science,
it's about education,

00:02:57.070 --> 00:02:58.150 align:middle line:90%
it's about achievement.

00:02:58.150 --> 00:02:59.900 align:middle line:84%
It's about, this is
the right way to do it

00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:02.483 align:middle line:84%
and you're married by this age
and you have this many children

00:03:02.483 --> 00:03:04.160 align:middle line:84%
by this-- like,
they had beliefs.

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:08.580 align:middle line:84%
And as I found myself
listening to those,

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:11.100 align:middle line:90%
it was like a battle to belong.

00:03:11.100 --> 00:03:14.522 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Did you feel
internally and intuitively

00:03:14.522 --> 00:03:17.350 align:middle line:90%
that that wasn't right?

00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:20.730 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: I don't know
that I ever at that age

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:23.070 align:middle line:90%
could hear my own voice.

00:03:23.070 --> 00:03:24.490 align:middle line:84%
Because ever since
I was little, I

00:03:24.490 --> 00:03:27.020 align:middle line:84%
was looking to them to take
care of me and love me.

00:03:27.020 --> 00:03:30.602 align:middle line:84%
And so I learned very
quickly how to please others.

00:03:30.602 --> 00:03:32.310 align:middle line:84%
All I wanted was their
love and approval.

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:33.232 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Don't we all?

00:03:33.232 --> 00:03:33.940 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Right?

00:03:33.940 --> 00:03:34.481 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:03:34.481 --> 00:03:36.540 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: And so I think
from a very young age

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:40.300 align:middle line:84%
we learn as children what makes
people laugh, what has them

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:43.510 align:middle line:84%
give us a hug,
what gives us love.

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:44.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:03:44.070 --> 00:03:44.920 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: And so
I think what we're

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:46.870 align:middle line:84%
doing is we're listening
to their voices

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:49.460 align:middle line:84%
and by the time we get
older, in high school,

00:03:49.460 --> 00:03:52.860 align:middle line:84%
we're listening to our peers'
voices louder than our own.

00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:54.654 align:middle line:90%
Anything to fit in, right?

00:03:54.654 --> 00:03:55.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, yes.

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:55.990 align:middle line:90%
Fiercely.

00:03:55.990 --> 00:03:57.790 align:middle line:84%
And it's a matter of
survival sometimes.

00:03:57.790 --> 00:03:58.770 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: It is a
matter of survival.

00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:00.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If I don't fit in here,
then I'm going be ostracized

00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:02.980 align:middle line:84%
and not liked, and it's
going to go back to all that.

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:03.220 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:03.970 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Yeah.

00:04:03.970 --> 00:04:07.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so you had
that experience as a child,

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:11.160 align:middle line:84%
but when you got to medicine,
you followed the routine

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:13.907 align:middle line:84%
and you went to medical
school and you did what you--

00:04:13.907 --> 00:04:15.240 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: I was a good soldier.

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:16.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: A good girl.

00:04:16.310 --> 00:04:19.839 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: I was so good that my
dad wanted me to be an engineer

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:21.339 align:middle line:84%
and my mom wanted
me to be a doctor.

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:23.540 align:middle line:84%
And as soon as I figured
out they weren't mutually

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:26.472 align:middle line:90%
exclusive, I did both of them.

00:04:26.472 --> 00:04:28.630 align:middle line:84%
Like, of course I'll
please the world here.

00:04:28.630 --> 00:04:29.410 align:middle line:90%
Of course.

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:32.610 align:middle line:84%
And also, I mean, I had a
love and an ease with math

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:35.800 align:middle line:84%
and science and all of
that, and I loved people.

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:38.450 align:middle line:84%
So it just seemed
like the right fit.

00:04:38.450 --> 00:04:40.000 align:middle line:84%
But then when I
got in, I started

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.080 align:middle line:90%
listening to my patients.

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:45.890 align:middle line:84%
And they would say things
to me like, you know doc,

00:04:45.890 --> 00:04:47.457 align:middle line:84%
thanks so-- I worked
in the hospital.

00:04:47.457 --> 00:04:49.540 align:middle line:84%
So it would be heart
attacks, strokes, pneumonias,

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:52.700 align:middle line:84%
the things that really
get people intubated.

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:54.200 align:middle line:84%
And so when they'd
come out and we'd

00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:56.980 align:middle line:84%
have them medically stabilized
they would say things like,

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:00.340 align:middle line:84%
doc, thank you for helping
me with this heart attack,

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:02.790 align:middle line:84%
but please don't discharge
me, because I can't go back

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:05.530 align:middle line:84%
to that toxic relationship
and environment.

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:07.196 align:middle line:90%
That's what's killing me.

00:05:07.196 --> 00:05:08.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You heard it again.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:09.653 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: And I heard it again.

00:05:09.653 --> 00:05:11.940 align:middle line:84%
And then I'd see them again
six months, a year later.

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:12.652 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, wow.

00:05:12.652 --> 00:05:14.110 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: And I
thought to myself,

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:15.470 align:middle line:90%
am I really helping them?

00:05:15.470 --> 00:05:18.120 align:middle line:84%
Of course I'm helping them
through an acute crisis.

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:20.280 align:middle line:90%
But am I really helping them?

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:22.820 align:middle line:84%
Like, am I helping them
solve the underlying issues

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:25.750 align:middle line:84%
so they don't have
to be here again?

00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:29.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And you realized that
you weren't in that level.

00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:33.220 align:middle line:84%
So how did you bridge the gap
to being able to actually--

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:36.455 align:middle line:84%
because you're an internal
medicine doctor, not

00:05:36.455 --> 00:05:39.420 align:middle line:84%
a therapist, a psychologist,
and all of that.

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:41.660 align:middle line:90%
But yet they are very linked.

00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:45.130 align:middle line:84%
How linked is the
gut to not speaking?

00:05:45.130 --> 00:05:45.970 align:middle line:90%
What do you see?

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:48.410 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: So there
are so many nerves.

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:51.980 align:middle line:84%
A majority of your nerves,
like, major amounts in your skin

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:54.340 align:middle line:84%
and in your GI
tract, or your gut.

00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:56.900 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of times the
way stress shows up

00:05:56.900 --> 00:05:59.251 align:middle line:84%
is-- have you ever heard that,
a little kid, all the way

00:05:59.251 --> 00:06:00.250 align:middle line:90%
from when you're little.

00:06:00.250 --> 00:06:01.750 align:middle line:90%
Mom, I have a tummy ache.

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:02.747 align:middle line:90%
I can't go to school.

00:06:02.747 --> 00:06:03.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:03.930 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:05.650 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: And the parent
will be like, oh, you just

00:06:05.650 --> 00:06:06.630 align:middle line:90%
don't want to go to school.

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:07.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:07.673 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: No.

00:06:07.673 --> 00:06:10.090 align:middle line:84%
It's because the child
is experiencing something

00:06:10.090 --> 00:06:12.190 align:middle line:84%
that they're resisting
or upset about,

00:06:12.190 --> 00:06:15.150 align:middle line:84%
and their stomach is turning,
they're getting these signals.

00:06:15.150 --> 00:06:18.220 align:middle line:84%
The only way they know how to
describe it is my tummy hurts.

00:06:18.220 --> 00:06:18.720 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:21.110 align:middle line:90%
It's not a doctor tummy ache.

00:06:21.110 --> 00:06:24.690 align:middle line:84%
It's a sit down and can we
talk about this tummy ache?

00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:26.360 align:middle line:84%
And so I think it
starts very young.

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:30.090 align:middle line:84%
When you're in college, I saw it
play out as hives before exams.

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:31.480 align:middle line:90%
Have you ever heard of people--

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:31.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:32.688 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Right?

00:06:32.688 --> 00:06:35.790 align:middle line:84%
Breaking out in hives
for finals week.

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:37.560 align:middle line:84%
As we get older, I've
noticed that some

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:40.120 align:middle line:84%
of the most common ways that
it shows up in my clients

00:06:40.120 --> 00:06:46.590 align:middle line:84%
are acid reflux,
diarrhea, constipation.

00:06:46.590 --> 00:06:50.640 align:middle line:84%
Some semblance of just, like,
not feeling OK in your gut.

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:51.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:53.460 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about the
acid reflux for a second,

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:55.600 align:middle line:84%
because there's millions
and millions of people

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:59.180 align:middle line:84%
that take acid
reflux medications.

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:03.680 align:middle line:84%
And it's masking the symptom
of the actual issue that

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:05.010 align:middle line:90%
might be going on.

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:06.760 align:middle line:84%
Is there a percentage
of people that you

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:08.790 align:middle line:84%
would say that
truly have the acid,

00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:12.790 align:middle line:84%
or is it really, truly
related to the emotion?

00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:15.620 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: So it's
an and, right?

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:18.430 align:middle line:84%
So I do believe that there
are physical reasons depending

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:21.460 align:middle line:84%
on what you ate last
night or drank last night.

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:24.220 align:middle line:90%


00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:26.570 align:middle line:84%
Functional medicine
is a kind of medicine

00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:30.030 align:middle line:84%
that really looks into
gluten, dairy, you know,

00:07:30.030 --> 00:07:33.380 align:middle line:84%
how do all these things
impact your system?

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:36.050 align:middle line:84%
So there can definitely
be physical causes,

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:37.549 align:middle line:84%
what you're putting
in your body.

00:07:37.549 --> 00:07:39.090 align:middle line:84%
There's also mechanical
causes, which

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:42.500 align:middle line:84%
would be, like, your valve at
the bottom of your esophagus

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:43.760 align:middle line:90%
is loose, right?

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:46.590 align:middle line:90%
That's going to let up acid.

00:07:46.590 --> 00:07:50.570 align:middle line:84%
There also can be
anxiety and stress

00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:54.500 align:middle line:84%
that causes people to have
their body be over stimulated

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:59.790 align:middle line:84%
and be ready to run, that
causes that adrenaline response.

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:01.249 align:middle line:84%
I don't really know
the percentage.

00:08:01.249 --> 00:08:03.081 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't be able to
give you a percentage.

00:08:03.081 --> 00:08:04.720 align:middle line:84%
But what I can tell
you is it usually

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.620 align:middle line:84%
is a combination of
all of these things.

00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:09.330 align:middle line:84%
Because as soon as someone-- we
don't know what comes first--

00:08:09.330 --> 00:08:12.315 align:middle line:84%
but as soon as they
start feeling that acid,

00:08:12.315 --> 00:08:14.190 align:middle line:84%
either they start getting
nervous and worried

00:08:14.190 --> 00:08:15.350 align:middle line:90%
and catastrophizing.

00:08:15.350 --> 00:08:16.730 align:middle line:90%
It all works together.

00:08:16.730 --> 00:08:19.260 align:middle line:84%
Now were they nervous,
worried, and catastrophizing,

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:20.450 align:middle line:90%
and then they got it?

00:08:20.450 --> 00:08:21.410 align:middle line:90%
I'm not usually sure.

00:08:21.410 --> 00:08:23.280 align:middle line:84%
But I know that it
all works together.

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:23.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:26.803 align:middle line:84%
And so do see a certain
amount of children?

00:08:26.803 --> 00:08:27.770 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Mm hmm.

00:08:27.770 --> 00:08:29.145 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And when
you see children

00:08:29.145 --> 00:08:31.970 align:middle line:84%
that have
gastrointestinal issues,

00:08:31.970 --> 00:08:36.054 align:middle line:84%
do you talk to the parents about
the emotional issues behind it?

00:08:36.054 --> 00:08:36.970 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Absolutely.

00:08:36.970 --> 00:08:37.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You have to, right?

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:39.725 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: But more than
talking to them, what I do

00:08:39.725 --> 00:08:44.059 align:middle line:84%
is I have them watch a session
of me working with their child.

00:08:44.059 --> 00:08:46.680 align:middle line:84%
And so the child will
just be talking to me

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:48.630 align:middle line:84%
and I'll have them
coloring, and we'll get up

00:08:48.630 --> 00:08:50.331 align:middle line:84%
and we'll start
shaking and dancing.

00:08:50.331 --> 00:08:52.080 align:middle line:84%
If they're feeling
something in their body

00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:52.890 align:middle line:84%
and they don't
know what to do, we

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:54.370 align:middle line:90%
get them to shake it all out.

00:08:54.370 --> 00:08:56.830 align:middle line:84%
And then we stop and I
have them feel their body.

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:59.494 align:middle line:84%
Children are very
connected to their body.

00:08:59.494 --> 00:09:00.910 align:middle line:84%
They don't have
all the strategies

00:09:00.910 --> 00:09:03.410 align:middle line:84%
we've got in place to make
sure everybody likes us.

00:09:03.410 --> 00:09:04.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:04.550 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Right?

00:09:04.550 --> 00:09:05.674 align:middle line:90%
They're just not inhibited.

00:09:05.674 --> 00:09:06.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:09:06.990 --> 00:09:09.240 align:middle line:84%
And so after we do
some of these exercises

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:12.590 align:middle line:84%
then I pick their favorite
song, we put it on,

00:09:12.590 --> 00:09:14.130 align:middle line:90%
and I have them dance their way.

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:15.720 align:middle line:84%
And we talk about all of the
things we're grateful for,

00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:17.636 align:middle line:84%
and we fill our bodies
back up with everything

00:09:17.636 --> 00:09:18.990 align:middle line:90%
we're happy about.

00:09:18.990 --> 00:09:21.730 align:middle line:84%
And so the parent can
see different skills.

00:09:21.730 --> 00:09:25.230 align:middle line:84%
I really think it's that parents
don't have this skill set,

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:25.730 align:middle line:90%
you know?

00:09:25.730 --> 00:09:29.810 align:middle line:84%
How does the body work with
these physical ailments?

00:09:29.810 --> 00:09:33.320 align:middle line:84%
And so I think what people
have begun to believe

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:37.762 align:middle line:84%
is that physical ailments
always have a physical cause.

00:09:37.762 --> 00:09:39.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:42.814 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: And I
believe that you always

00:09:42.814 --> 00:09:44.480 align:middle line:84%
have to get checked
out by doctor first.

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:46.430 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Wait, do you mean
emotional ailments have

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:48.930 align:middle line:84%
a physical cause, or physical
ailments have a physical cause?

00:09:48.930 --> 00:09:49.931 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: So it's both.

00:09:49.931 --> 00:09:50.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:09:50.430 --> 00:09:52.304 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: Sometimes
it's a physical ailment.

00:09:52.304 --> 00:09:57.550 align:middle line:84%
If I am, you know, lacking a
certain vitamin or nutrient,

00:09:57.550 --> 00:09:59.500 align:middle line:84%
B12 or something
like that, I may

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:01.490 align:middle line:84%
have physical symptoms
resulting from that.

00:10:01.490 --> 00:10:01.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:10:01.990 --> 00:10:04.300 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: So there may
be a physical cause.

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:06.560 align:middle line:84%
But that's the
assumption in medicine.

00:10:06.560 --> 00:10:08.660 align:middle line:84%
But what I find is
when someone's anxious,

00:10:08.660 --> 00:10:11.620 align:middle line:84%
anxiety is a huge problem
in our culture, right?

00:10:11.620 --> 00:10:13.016 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:10:13.016 --> 00:10:14.640 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: People
don't sleep at night,

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:17.230 align:middle line:84%
so they put themselves
on all this medication.

00:10:17.230 --> 00:10:20.430 align:middle line:84%
But when I actually asked them
what keeps them up at night,

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.122 align:middle line:90%
it's not a lack of--

00:10:22.122 --> 00:10:22.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Vitamins.

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:24.550 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: Sleep--
no, sleep medication.

00:10:24.550 --> 00:10:25.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, yeah.

00:10:25.300 --> 00:10:27.880 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: It is this
thing that they've

00:10:27.880 --> 00:10:30.980 align:middle line:84%
been unable to say, it's
the grief that they've never

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:33.440 align:middle line:84%
been able to let go of,
it's the conversation

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:35.155 align:middle line:84%
that they don't have
the guts to have.

00:10:35.155 --> 00:10:36.810 align:middle line:84%
They're in a toxic
work environment,

00:10:36.810 --> 00:10:39.180 align:middle line:84%
they're in a relationship
that's long since expired.

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:39.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:10:39.750 --> 00:10:39.940 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Right?

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:40.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, absolutely.

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:42.300 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: When you really
get to the root of it.

00:10:42.300 --> 00:10:44.100 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That keeps you
up, and it loops and loops

00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:46.516 align:middle line:84%
and loops and loops until you
exhaust yourself or never do

00:10:46.516 --> 00:10:48.670 align:middle line:84%
fall asleep, and the next
morning you wake up so

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:51.020 align:middle line:84%
exhausted that you have to
take something to stay awake.

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:51.645 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Yes.

00:10:51.645 --> 00:10:53.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah, absolutely.

00:10:53.150 --> 00:10:53.690 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:10:53.690 --> 00:10:55.315 align:middle line:84%
I've had many friends
in that situation

00:10:55.315 --> 00:10:58.160 align:middle line:84%
and it gets just in a
very, very bad place,

00:10:58.160 --> 00:10:59.250 align:middle line:90%
and you wind up in rehab.

00:10:59.250 --> 00:10:59.530 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Yep.

00:10:59.530 --> 00:11:00.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So, yeah.

00:11:00.120 --> 00:11:01.675 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: It goes out
of control pretty quick.

00:11:01.675 --> 00:11:02.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Mm hmm.

00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:03.081 align:middle line:90%
Very fast.

00:11:03.081 --> 00:11:05.080 align:middle line:84%
Well, I want you to take
a look at Dr. Neha here

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:07.410 align:middle line:84%
talking at a Ted Talk, and
she explains a lot of this.

00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:07.910 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:11:07.910 --> 00:11:08.710 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:11:08.710 --> 00:11:12.100 align:middle line:84%
-And what struck me the
most was my patients

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:14.660 align:middle line:90%
weren't afraid of dying.

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:17.125 align:middle line:84%
They were afraid that they
had never lived fully.

00:11:17.125 --> 00:11:20.690 align:middle line:90%


00:11:20.690 --> 00:11:26.560 align:middle line:84%
So they taught me what 13 years
of medical education did not.

00:11:26.560 --> 00:11:28.950 align:middle line:84%
That it wasn't
just the anatomical

00:11:28.950 --> 00:11:31.060 align:middle line:84%
and the physiological
breakdown of their bodies

00:11:31.060 --> 00:11:32.410 align:middle line:90%
that I was dealing with.

00:11:32.410 --> 00:11:38.060 align:middle line:84%
Something had begun
long, long ago.

00:11:38.060 --> 00:11:40.470 align:middle line:84%
They had either stopped
listening to themselves

00:11:40.470 --> 00:11:43.940 align:middle line:84%
and their body like
Brandon, they had shut down

00:11:43.940 --> 00:11:47.500 align:middle line:84%
their emotions
like Juan, or they

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:53.850 align:middle line:84%
had given up all the things
that matter to them like Lily.

00:11:53.850 --> 00:11:58.940 align:middle line:84%
And then somehow this
catastrophic event happened,

00:11:58.940 --> 00:12:03.780 align:middle line:84%
and they showed up
metaphorically on their knees

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:06.710 align:middle line:84%
with all of us
together realizing

00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:11.090 align:middle line:84%
that these things
were all connected.

00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:15.540 align:middle line:84%
So I wish I could tell
you that I am smart enough

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:22.710 align:middle line:84%
to have used these patients'
stories and learned myself.

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:26.640 align:middle line:90%
But the truth is, I wasn't.

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:29.930 align:middle line:84%
I had this awakening
that began in me,

00:12:29.930 --> 00:12:32.700 align:middle line:84%
and I knew that this authentic
connection that I was creating

00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:37.990 align:middle line:84%
for them was something I needed
to take long before they showed

00:12:37.990 --> 00:12:38.950 align:middle line:90%
up in the ICU.

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:43.420 align:middle line:84%
How could I impact
them long before?

00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:45.930 align:middle line:84%
Except I wanted to
squash that thought.

00:12:45.930 --> 00:12:48.720 align:middle line:84%
Listen, I had great
security and stability

00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:51.632 align:middle line:84%
with a partnership
and a paycheck, OK?

00:12:51.632 --> 00:12:53.090 align:middle line:84%
People paid me to
take care of them

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:55.140 align:middle line:90%
after everything had happened.

00:12:55.140 --> 00:13:00.330 align:middle line:84%
Would anyone pay me
to do what I loved?

00:13:00.330 --> 00:13:04.600 align:middle line:84%
So I began numbing
out my own symptoms.

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:06.850 align:middle line:84%
I had a perfected
equation to get me

00:13:06.850 --> 00:13:09.110 align:middle line:90%
through my hospital shifts.

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:13.820 align:middle line:84%
It was two ice cold 16 ounce
Mountain Dews plus a king size

00:13:13.820 --> 00:13:18.290 align:middle line:84%
Snickers bar, and I could get
through any shift you gave me.

00:13:18.290 --> 00:13:20.774 align:middle line:84%
So I heard some laughter out
there and I want to know,

00:13:20.774 --> 00:13:22.440 align:middle line:84%
I think that's coming
from the students.

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:27.510 align:middle line:84%
Because you know what it takes
to get through finals week.

00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:29.050 align:middle line:84%
So you have your
own equation, and I

00:13:29.050 --> 00:13:31.932 align:middle line:84%
want you to think
about what that is.

00:13:31.932 --> 00:13:35.340 align:middle line:84%
You know this isn't
going to end well, right?

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:36.810 align:middle line:90%
So here I am.

00:13:36.810 --> 00:13:37.740 align:middle line:90%
I burned out.

00:13:37.740 --> 00:13:42.530 align:middle line:84%
I was on medical
leave June 17, 2004.

00:13:42.530 --> 00:13:45.370 align:middle line:84%
And I had to ask
myself the questions

00:13:45.370 --> 00:13:48.750 align:middle line:84%
that I had so often
asked other people.

00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:50.410 align:middle line:90%
Neha, why you?

00:13:50.410 --> 00:13:53.660 align:middle line:90%
Why burn out, and why now?

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:55.540 align:middle line:84%
What message had it
come to give you?

00:13:55.540 --> 00:13:58.060 align:middle line:90%


00:13:58.060 --> 00:14:01.899 align:middle line:84%
The answers didn't
come right away for me.

00:14:01.899 --> 00:14:03.440 align:middle line:84%
I checked it out
with some colleagues

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:05.320 align:middle line:84%
to see if they had ever
experienced something

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:08.320 align:middle line:90%
like this.

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:11.330 align:middle line:84%
I then began to listen
to my mind and my body,

00:14:11.330 --> 00:14:14.190 align:middle line:90%
and I started journaling.

00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:19.976 align:middle line:84%
And what I read on those
pages scared me to death.

00:14:19.976 --> 00:14:21.350 align:middle line:84%
I didn't just want
to help people

00:14:21.350 --> 00:14:23.800 align:middle line:84%
before they ended
up in the hospital.

00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:27.590 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to create
self-care in health care.

00:14:27.590 --> 00:14:30.830 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to help
heal the healers.

00:14:30.830 --> 00:14:33.710 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to become a
master in communication

00:14:33.710 --> 00:14:36.880 align:middle line:84%
and combine it with my
knowledge of health,

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:41.540 align:middle line:84%
and I wanted to use that
to go and bridge nations.

00:14:41.540 --> 00:14:43.027 align:middle line:90%
That scared me.

00:14:43.027 --> 00:14:43.860 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:46.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you are known as the
Doctor of Communication, which

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:47.980 align:middle line:90%
I mentioned earlier.

00:14:47.980 --> 00:14:51.060 align:middle line:84%
So what type of signals do
you feel in your own body

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:53.077 align:middle line:84%
when you're not
speaking your truth?

00:14:53.077 --> 00:14:54.660 align:middle line:84%
I mean, just to use
you as an example.

00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:57.950 align:middle line:84%
Because I know in my body,
it's like my intestines

00:14:57.950 --> 00:15:00.290 align:middle line:90%
get turned into knots and bows.

00:15:00.290 --> 00:15:03.717 align:middle line:84%
So what do you feel when
you're not speaking your truth?

00:15:03.717 --> 00:15:05.300 align:middle line:84%
Back when you didn't
speak your truth.

00:15:05.300 --> 00:15:06.816 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: No, I still feel it.

00:15:06.816 --> 00:15:07.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:08.520 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Yes.

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:10.100 align:middle line:90%
Now it's a friendly reminder.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:13.140 align:middle line:84%
Back then it was a whisper
until it became paralyzing,

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:17.850 align:middle line:84%
which is the throat constriction
turned cutting off my air.

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:22.730 align:middle line:84%
And now at the slightest
hint of throat constricting,

00:15:22.730 --> 00:15:26.440 align:middle line:84%
heart racing, and
stomach turning,

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:29.570 align:middle line:84%
it's my signal that I've
just not spoken my truth.

00:15:29.570 --> 00:15:34.060 align:middle line:84%
And in that moment I ask myself,
do I need to pause and go back

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:37.360 align:middle line:84%
and readdress this,
renegotiate what just happened?

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:39.290 align:middle line:84%
Or is this something,
like, what was it

00:15:39.290 --> 00:15:40.940 align:middle line:90%
about this that I wasn't saying?

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:42.580 align:middle line:90%
So my body tells me right away.

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:44.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so do you
find yourself speaking

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:46.630 align:middle line:84%
your truth more and
more and more now?

00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:47.730 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Absolutely.

00:15:47.730 --> 00:15:50.740 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of like, the way I
describe this experience is,

00:15:50.740 --> 00:15:52.770 align:middle line:84%
I've become a
self-cleaning oven.

00:15:52.770 --> 00:15:53.770 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:15:53.770 --> 00:15:56.600 align:middle line:84%
It's like, you know,
something happens.

00:15:56.600 --> 00:15:58.550 align:middle line:84%
And what I do is,
I don't go talking

00:15:58.550 --> 00:15:59.780 align:middle line:90%
to everyone about everything.

00:15:59.780 --> 00:16:01.630 align:middle line:90%
But I have this three time rule.

00:16:01.630 --> 00:16:02.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:16:02.330 --> 00:16:04.704 align:middle line:84%
>>SANGWAN: The first time
something happens, I notice it.

00:16:04.704 --> 00:16:05.870 align:middle line:90%
Mm.

00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:06.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:08.070 align:middle line:84%
The second time it
happens, I mentally

00:16:08.070 --> 00:16:10.660 align:middle line:84%
put it in my mental
filing cabinet.

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:11.830 align:middle line:90%
I might need this.

00:16:11.830 --> 00:16:16.048 align:middle line:84%
The third time it
happens I say, hey Lisa.

00:16:16.048 --> 00:16:19.045 align:middle line:84%
You know, I wanted to talk to
you about yesterday at lunch,

00:16:19.045 --> 00:16:20.150 align:middle line:90%
our meeting.

00:16:20.150 --> 00:16:21.700 align:middle line:90%
And it'll take about 15 minutes.

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:23.420 align:middle line:84%
I'm wondering when's
a good time for you.

00:16:23.420 --> 00:16:25.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, wow.

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:26.560 align:middle line:90%
You actually go right for it.

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:29.730 align:middle line:84%
I'm sure I was raised with that
good girl attitude as well,

00:16:29.730 --> 00:16:33.240 align:middle line:84%
because I recall situations
in conversations,

00:16:33.240 --> 00:16:35.660 align:middle line:84%
I wish I could have said that
and I wanted to say this,

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:37.140 align:middle line:90%
and I didn't.

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:39.270 align:middle line:84%
So in your body, so
you're teaching people

00:16:39.270 --> 00:16:42.280 align:middle line:84%
to really feel that
sensation in your body.

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:44.380 align:middle line:84%
Because we know
when it's not truth.

00:16:44.380 --> 00:16:45.120 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: We do.

00:16:45.120 --> 00:16:46.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it
actually sometimes,

00:16:46.590 --> 00:16:49.770 align:middle line:84%
when other people are
as communicative as you

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:52.830 align:middle line:84%
are and say exactly
what they're feeling,

00:16:52.830 --> 00:16:55.640 align:middle line:84%
it makes me feel awkward
when they say that.

00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:56.330 align:middle line:90%
>>SANGWAN: Yeah.

00:16:56.330 --> 00:16:58.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's so ingrained in me.

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:00.080 align:middle line:90%
But I want a step.

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:03.080 align:middle line:84%
I want a process
that can show me

00:17:03.080 --> 00:17:07.010 align:middle line:84%
how to nip it right
away, how to do that.

00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:09.950 align:middle line:84%
Because that's going to be
key for me in the future.

00:17:09.950 --> 00:17:13.460 align:middle line:84%
So say your boss,
someone who you know.

00:17:13.460 --> 00:17:14.911 align:middle line:90%
You don't want to get fired.

00:17:14.911 --> 00:17:16.869 align:middle line:84%
This would lead to, like,
you losing their job,

00:17:16.869 --> 00:17:18.010 align:middle line:90%
blah, blah, blah.

00:17:18.010 --> 00:17:21.914 align:middle line:84%
How do you say to them, look,
you're not treating me nicely.

00:17:21.914 --> 00:17:24.960 align:middle line:90%


00:17:24.960 --> 00:17:26.420 align:middle line:84%
How do you say
that to your boss?

